1
00:00:02,208 --> 00:00:05,758
Tonight's talk is on the six sense spheres.

2
00:00:06,902 --> 00:00:17,111
You may remember that in the final section of the Satipatthana Sutta, the section on Dhammas, Buddha asks us to contemplate various of his teachings.

3
00:00:17,867 --> 00:00:23,117
He starts with the hindrances, then the canda or aggregates which we looked at last night.

4
00:00:23,978 --> 00:00:27,004
Next, he lists the six sense spheres.

5
00:00:28,367 --> 00:00:37,564
All of these direct our attention to the origin and nature of suffering and offer us means of escape, but each in their own unique way.

6
00:00:38,893 --> 00:00:46,484
The teaching on the hindrances asks us to get to know the moment to moment experience of the forces that disturb our peace of mind.

7
00:00:47,826 --> 00:00:51,051
We're becoming familiar with their physical and mental expression.

8
00:00:51,932 --> 00:00:54,996
The more deeply we know them, the less they dominate us.

9
00:00:56,097 --> 00:01:04,750
Our bodies may vibrate with their energy, we perceive how they are tempting us, but we can make an independent decision about how to act.

10
00:01:06,112 --> 00:01:21,456
At times, we may decide to use the energetic pathways they stimulate, for example, to use aversion to invigorate assertiveness when we're feeling threatened, use desire to enthuse us to accomplish something beneficial.

11
00:01:22,566 --> 00:01:31,739
At other times it's a question of letting go of their energy moment after moment until this episode of the hindrance burns itself out.

12
00:01:33,141 --> 00:01:42,533
This first of the Dhammas listed in the Satipatthana Sutta shows us a very immediate and dynamic method of freeing ourselves from suffering.

13
00:01:45,096 --> 00:01:50,143
The teaching of the hindrances can be likened to skills training for a spiritual warrior

14
00:01:51,135 --> 00:01:58,847
By contrast, I think of the next teaching as a more composed enterprise, such as a scientific expedition.

15
00:02:00,129 --> 00:02:04,076
This is the teaching on the canda, the five aggregates of clinging.

16
00:02:05,418 --> 00:02:15,996
We're not being threatened by a hindrance here, but we're deliberately bringing ourselves into the zone of their influence, in order to get a feel for what binds us to suffering.

17
00:02:17,275 --> 00:02:28,298
We let attention dwell on our bodies, for example, to experience how we get drawn into anxieties as the tendency to think of this as my body comes to mind.

18
00:02:29,560 --> 00:02:33,425
One moment the breath is registered as simply a physical sensation.

19
00:02:34,366 --> 00:02:40,034
Next moment we've added a lorryload of meaning to this, all tethered to thoughts of me and mine.

20
00:02:41,417 --> 00:02:48,548
Similarly for all the other Kanda, we experience their allure and then the pain of entrapment.

21
00:02:49,688 --> 00:02:53,474
And we say to ourselves, I'm not going to get caught like that again.

22
00:02:54,704 --> 00:03:01,794
Thus, the study of the Kanda strengthens the wisdom we need to avoid new entanglements with Dukkha.

23
00:03:04,278 --> 00:03:09,587
The teaching on the six sense spheres also has the nature of scientific inquiry.

24
00:03:10,889 --> 00:03:22,348
This time the focus is not just on how we tend to get trapped, which is what we're studying in the Kanda, but equally on finding the moment-to-moment pathway to freedom.

25
00:03:24,387 --> 00:03:33,719
The sense spheres direct our attention to the boundary between our internal subjective world and the external objective world.

26
00:03:35,423 --> 00:03:43,875
Resting attention here, we can experience the draw towards clinging and dukkha and the possibility of freedom and release.

27
00:03:45,097 --> 00:03:50,343
This is the choice on offer to us at each moment of sense contact.

28
00:03:51,336 --> 00:03:58,026
The better we get at recognizing these pathways, the more easily we choose the pathway to freedom.

29
00:04:01,312 --> 00:04:11,728
As with the teaching on the hindrances, this teaching on the sense spheres offers us a very dynamic, immediate tool for moment-to-moment release from suffering.

30
00:04:12,990 --> 00:04:19,420
In the case of the hindrances, we've been caught in a thick bramble of dukkha and we're fighting our way clear.

31
00:04:20,598 --> 00:04:27,146
In the case of the sense spheres, we're brushing up against a thicket and finding out how to steer clear.

32
00:04:28,369 --> 00:04:36,119
We're releasing ourselves from the delusion that lets us get caught in the first place.

33
00:04:36,139 --> 00:04:40,125
The spheres are made up of the five physical senses.

34
00:04:40,476 --> 00:04:45,041
sight, hearing, taste, smell and touch.

35
00:04:46,023 --> 00:04:56,293
These can all be described as doorways connecting us to the external world of visible objects, sounds, flavours, aromas and tactile sensations.

36
00:04:57,776 --> 00:05:06,264
Normally when we say sixth sense we mean an intuition or gut feeling, something outside of the normal sensory realm.

37
00:05:07,274 --> 00:05:15,083
But in Buddhism, the sixth sense is the doorway to the ordinary experiences of thought and memory and emotion.

38
00:05:16,564 --> 00:05:26,134
The sixth sense sphere comprises the conscious mind and the sense object that the mind perceives.

39
00:05:27,836 --> 00:05:31,982
This is how the Buddha advises us to contemplate the sense spheres.

40
00:05:33,785 --> 00:05:38,031
How does one contemplate Dhammas in terms of the six sense spheres?

41
00:05:39,151 --> 00:05:44,759
One knows the eye and forms, and the fetter that arises dependent on both.

42
00:05:46,262 --> 00:05:52,290
One knows the ears and sounds, and the fetter that arises dependent on both.

43
00:05:53,672 --> 00:05:56,214
And so on for all the six senses.

44
00:05:58,286 --> 00:06:08,021
We'll come to the fetter in a moment, but first let's look at the guidance to know the eye and visible objects, the ear and sounds, etc.

45
00:06:09,583 --> 00:06:22,422
This may sound pretty straightforward, but in fact it points us towards quite a mysterious aspect of life, one which has puzzled scientists and sages for centuries.

46
00:06:24,257 --> 00:06:29,125
Normally, we would only be aware of the forms, sounds, etc.

47
00:06:29,807 --> 00:06:32,350
We see a cat, we hear a bell.

48
00:06:33,833 --> 00:06:39,961
But when we're being mindful of the sense spheres, we also know we are seeing and hearing.

49
00:06:41,444 --> 00:06:47,994
This makes us more aware of sense contact as the interface between our inner and outer worlds.

50
00:06:49,336 --> 00:06:52,341
It helps break down the illusion of separation.

51
00:06:53,653 --> 00:06:55,677
The cat isn't just out there.

52
00:06:55,697 --> 00:06:57,802
I am seeing it.

53
00:06:59,084 --> 00:07:04,536
I've let it into my mind where it can generate all kinds of thoughts and feelings about cats.

54
00:07:05,678 --> 00:07:10,870
I might not want to think of any of these thoughts, but I can't help it now that the cat's got in.

55
00:07:13,060 --> 00:07:18,464
I sensed this one time as I was meditating and became aware of a bird singing.

56
00:07:19,365 --> 00:07:20,307
It was a black bird.

57
00:07:20,968 --> 00:07:24,651
You know the way they whistle a tune and after a pause a different one.

58
00:07:26,452 --> 00:07:34,141
I noticed how my mood lightened each time I heard the notes and how eagerly I was anticipating the next trill during the pauses.

59
00:07:35,862 --> 00:07:37,343
Suddenly the thought occurred to me.

60
00:07:38,144 --> 00:07:39,005
Where is the bird?

61
00:07:39,906 --> 00:07:41,869
Is he in here or out there?

62
00:07:42,810 --> 00:07:45,954
Intellectually, of course, I knew the bird was outside of me.

63
00:07:47,036 --> 00:07:51,221
But I'd suddenly realised the key role I was playing in our interaction.

64
00:07:52,283 --> 00:08:01,036
It was my ears and my brain that were doing all their magical processing work to detect the sound and register it in my mind.

65
00:08:02,557 --> 00:08:05,882
So it seemed we were both co-creators of the sound.

66
00:08:06,891 --> 00:08:24,494
This gave me a graphic illustration of the Buddha's teaching on the sense spheres and how attending carefully to our sense data can break down the illusion of there being a me who is in here and in control of my world and totally separate from the world out there.

67
00:08:26,737 --> 00:08:30,341
On top of that, it seemed the bird was determining my moods and thoughts.

68
00:08:31,302 --> 00:08:34,265
When he chose to sing, I would feel glad.

69
00:08:34,937 --> 00:08:38,102
When he chose to pause, I would start getting a bit anxious.

70
00:08:39,024 --> 00:08:42,932
So from the emotional point of view, he was in charge, not me.

71
00:08:45,797 --> 00:08:56,355
Both of these insights gave me tiny glimpses of the Buddha's teaching on anatta, that the sense of ourselves as permanent, substantial and in control of our lives is an illusion.

72
00:08:57,500 --> 00:09:05,150
Listening mindfully to that bird song had taught me that there wasn't any clear dividing line between myself and the blackbird.

73
00:09:08,335 --> 00:09:12,081
I had a similar experience one time, gazing at a Buddha rupa.

74
00:09:13,702 --> 00:09:19,490
I was alone in the meditation hall, and for a while I was seeing the rupa in quite an ordinary way.

75
00:09:20,331 --> 00:09:26,802
Then suddenly, though I was still gazing at the image, my attention was drawn to the me who was gazing.

76
00:09:27,945 --> 00:09:31,971
Again I sensed the very active part I was playing in the process of seeing.

77
00:09:33,274 --> 00:09:40,346
Though the rupa was out there, it needed my attention to create the image that my consciousness was registering.

78
00:09:42,048 --> 00:09:46,034
I sensed my attention as creative, a form of goodwill.

79
00:09:46,960 --> 00:09:52,727
By choosing to attend to the Buddha Rupa, I was bringing this image into being for myself.

80
00:09:54,629 --> 00:10:04,243
At that moment I couldn't tell whether the image was really out there or whether my attention was actually creating the image and just imagining it to be out there.

81
00:10:05,804 --> 00:10:14,537
I realised that my subjective experience of the world could not be separated from what I normally thought of as the objective world out there.

82
00:10:15,817 --> 00:10:23,746
Curiously, I had experienced this insight as a child, wondering if other people really existed when I wasn't looking at them.

83
00:10:24,928 --> 00:10:33,320
I spent a while peeping through keyholes, wondering could I catch them magically coming into existence so as to perform for me.

84
00:10:34,642 --> 00:10:38,005
But after a while I realised that I could never catch them out that way.

85
00:10:38,826 --> 00:10:43,072
The moment I had seen them, it was already too late for my experiment.

86
00:10:45,111 --> 00:10:55,607
In Zen, the puzzle is captured in the story of two monks who are looking at a flag waving in the breeze and arguing about whether it is the flag or the wind that is moving.

87
00:10:56,590 --> 00:11:01,356
The teacher intervenes saying, neither the flag nor the wind are moving.

88
00:11:02,178 --> 00:11:04,302
It is only your minds that are moving.

89
00:11:06,154 --> 00:11:18,751
The conundrum has been debated in Western philosophy since it was posed by George Berkeley and is expressed in the question If a tree falls in the forest and no one hears it, does it make a sound?

90
00:11:20,693 --> 00:11:22,876
The question has puzzled physicists as well.

91
00:11:22,897 --> 00:11:33,410
A conversation between Albert Einstein and Niels Bohr is recorded where Einstein asked Bohr whether the moon exists when no one is looking at it.

92
00:11:35,077 --> 00:11:39,904
Bohr replied that no matter how hard he tried, he could not prove that it did exist.

93
00:11:41,908 --> 00:11:50,941
Einstein and Bohr's interest in the question would have been stirred by a recent peculiar finding in quantum physics, termed the observer effect.

94
00:11:52,464 --> 00:12:00,816
It applies to small subatomic particles that are the building clocks of our physical reality, electrons and protons for example.

95
00:12:02,315 --> 00:12:11,528
If you try to describe any of these according to its quantum equation, what you find is that it has the potential to be almost anywhere in the universe.

96
00:12:13,052 --> 00:12:15,455
The act of observation changes all that.

97
00:12:16,697 --> 00:12:19,902
It forces the particle to show up somewhere or other.

98
00:12:21,231 --> 00:12:27,259
This was first detected for electrons, those tiny particles that flow in every electrical current.

99
00:12:28,380 --> 00:12:39,013
If you try to pin down an electron and detect whether it goes through one specific place or another, it will behave as you expect and go through one pathway or the other.

100
00:12:40,033 --> 00:12:49,686
But if you don't switch on your detectors so you don't know which pathway it went through, it will behave as if it has simultaneously gone through both.

101
00:12:51,826 --> 00:12:59,827
Weird as this sounds, the phenomenon underlies your cell phone and remote control and almost every device you use nowadays.

102
00:13:01,342 --> 00:13:07,193
Basically, quantum mechanics describes what Einstein described as a very spooky world.

103
00:13:08,777 --> 00:13:11,562
Matter can be anywhere and everywhere at once.

104
00:13:12,423 --> 00:13:24,567
It can penetrate through solid barriers, particles make instantaneous communication with one another even over vast distances, and the observer effect, taken literally,

105
00:13:24,547 --> 00:13:33,019
That implies that subjective observation may actually be playing a huge role in determining the physical state of the world.

106
00:13:35,364 --> 00:13:40,211
Quantum physics describes a world which no one truly knows how to interpret.

107
00:13:41,452 --> 00:13:49,304
Most mainstream scientists ignore the deeper questions and follow Dirac's injunction to shut up and calculate.

108
00:13:50,432 --> 00:13:56,423
and perhaps I should also follow their lead and leave off trying to explain that spooky quantum world.

109
00:13:57,705 --> 00:14:14,212
But it is a big draw for me and as the teaching on the six sense spheres directs our attention to that mysterious interface between subjectivity and objectivity, which has also been thrown up by quantum physics, I couldn't resist the temptation.

110
00:14:15,761 --> 00:14:32,480
And I hope that drawing your attention to the mystery might entice you to rest attention at sense contact and let curiosity and wonder maintain your meditation on this so common aspect of life that we so easily skip over.

111
00:14:35,062 --> 00:14:39,086
However, let's go back to the teaching on the sense spheres.

112
00:14:40,956 --> 00:14:45,761
The Buddha taught that four things are needed in order to make sense contact.

113
00:14:46,722 --> 00:14:49,046
Two are part of the external world.

114
00:14:50,027 --> 00:14:55,232
The sense object itself, the sound, the aroma, the visible form, etc.

115
00:14:55,994 --> 00:14:58,416
and the medium that enables this to be sensed.

116
00:14:59,717 --> 00:15:03,302
For example, we need light to see a visible object.

117
00:15:03,741 --> 00:15:05,043
We won't see in the dark.

118
00:15:06,105 --> 00:15:10,068
The other components needed for sense contact are internal.

119
00:15:10,403 --> 00:15:14,528
We need our sensory apparatus, our eyes, ears, etc.

120
00:15:16,110 --> 00:15:18,113
Finally, we need attention.

121
00:15:19,475 --> 00:15:23,679
This is what had struck me so forcibly when I had looked at the Buddha Rupa.

122
00:15:24,642 --> 00:15:30,308
I realised my attention was a central and a necessary part of the image I was seeing.

123
00:15:32,231 --> 00:15:39,380
Thus, the sense spheres form that link between our internal world and the external world.

124
00:15:40,592 --> 00:15:45,561
The Buddha doesn't comment on the question of whether consciousness affects the external world.

125
00:15:46,503 --> 00:15:52,011
His focus is not on philosophy, but on the possibility of freeing ourselves from dukkha.

126
00:15:53,254 --> 00:15:56,740
But he certainly wants us to link the external and the internal.

127
00:15:57,741 --> 00:16:05,014
He doesn't want us to think in terms of cats and blackbirds and buddharupas as objects out there.

128
00:16:04,994 --> 00:16:12,921
He wants us to experience how our attention and sense organs combine with these to bring about sense contact.

129
00:16:14,402 --> 00:16:19,846
He wants us to experience the meeting point of the internal and external world.

130
00:16:22,249 --> 00:16:26,413
Sometimes the use of the passive voice in our noting words can help here.

131
00:16:27,312 --> 00:16:34,899
Instead of saying hearing, hearing as we listen to birdsong, we can say sound being heard.

132
00:16:36,178 --> 00:16:43,787
This is a more awkward phrase, but it helps us to take in the subjectivity of our experience.

133
00:16:43,807 --> 00:16:51,693
It directs attention to the all-important but ever so quiet knowing aspect of our experience.

134
00:16:51,714 --> 00:17:01,443
Our fascination with the external world of sounds and sights might fade for a while as we get drawn toward the mystery of consciousness itself.

135
00:17:08,224 --> 00:17:16,778
To deepen our understanding of the internal factors underlying sense contact, let's go back to the wheel of dependent origination.

136
00:17:18,402 --> 00:17:26,855
The sense spheres form the midsection of the wheel, and it's the first half of the wheel that describes our subjective role in sense contact.

137
00:17:27,936 --> 00:17:34,047
It all starts with Avijja, our misunderstanding about what leads to happiness and what to suffering.

138
00:17:35,343 --> 00:17:40,472
Avijja, ignorance, forms the breeding ground for unwholesome Sankaras.

139
00:17:41,815 --> 00:17:46,044
Sankaras are the habits of mind which push us into and through our lives.

140
00:17:47,165 --> 00:17:51,032
In order to exercise their driving power, they need to become conscious.

141
00:17:52,194 --> 00:17:57,164
The third link in the wheel lets us become conscious of the Sankara rooted in ignorance.

142
00:17:58,563 --> 00:18:02,930
For consciousness to manifest in the world we need both body and mind.

143
00:18:04,313 --> 00:18:10,303
Our bodies are part of the physical world of matter, our minds inhabit the world of thought and imagination.

144
00:18:11,664 --> 00:18:16,452
The pair are termed Nama-rupa and form the fourth link in the wheel.

145
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:22,663
Thus our Sankara habit drives our body as well as our mind.

146
00:18:23,790 --> 00:18:28,557
If we are habitually angry, our jaws and teeth may be clenched most of the time.

147
00:18:28,596 --> 00:18:34,183
If we worry habitually, our forehead will probably develop creases from frowning.

148
00:18:36,247 --> 00:18:39,991
The Sankara now needs to decide which of our senses to work through.

149
00:18:40,952 --> 00:18:43,276
So now we're up to the six sense spheres again.

150
00:18:44,877 --> 00:18:50,945
The next link in the wheel is their internal subjective component, the six sense doors.

151
00:18:52,039 --> 00:18:54,624
The Sankara can find its way through any of these.

152
00:18:54,644 --> 00:19:01,933
A Sankara of ill-will can listen morosely to a conversation waiting for something to disagree with.

153
00:19:02,934 --> 00:19:08,182
A Sankara of greed can look through our eyes searching for something to devour.

154
00:19:08,222 --> 00:19:18,477
Then the sense doors link up with the external world and this meeting place of the Sankara with the world forms the sixth link in the wheel.

155
00:19:18,517 --> 00:19:20,680
SENSE CONTACT

156
00:19:22,616 --> 00:19:26,763
A new bit of sense data impacts on our psycho-physical system.

157
00:19:27,625 --> 00:19:31,332
It could be a sound, it could be a sight, it could be a thought.

158
00:19:32,374 --> 00:19:40,288
We usually think of thoughts and emotions as part of our internal world, but they can also be objective.

159
00:19:41,398 --> 00:19:46,525
When greed finds its way into consciousness, the thought of ice cream can make us run to the fridge.

160
00:19:47,465 --> 00:19:53,693
When goodwill is established, that same thought can stir happy memories, joy and gratitude.

161
00:19:55,435 --> 00:20:04,707
When ill-will plants itself in consciousness and we sense the emotion of anger, it's easy to add the second arrow and hate ourselves for being angry.

162
00:20:05,934 --> 00:20:11,627
When compassion implants itself, the emotion of anger becomes something to care for tenderly.

163
00:20:12,710 --> 00:20:19,404
So thoughts and emotions can act as objects for whatever is appearing through the sense door.

164
00:20:21,258 --> 00:20:36,777
The teaching on the sense spheres directs our attention to this crucial mid-section of the wheel of dependent origination, where our sankara based in ignorance has found its way from our inner subjective world to the outer objective world.

165
00:20:38,098 --> 00:20:42,304
If we are not careful, a whole new pathway for dukkha opens up.

166
00:20:42,284 --> 00:20:53,172
But if we are mindful, then we have the opportunity to let that sankara fizzle its energy away, trying to get us to react while we steadfastly refuse.

167
00:20:55,192 --> 00:21:00,201
It helps to become curious about how our moods and emotions seem to colour the world.

168
00:21:01,183 --> 00:21:08,037
If we're in a flaming temper, we won't hear the bees buzzing in the same way as we would if we were in good humour.

169
00:21:08,538 --> 00:21:15,530
In fact, we probably won't hear them at all or any nature sounds because of the storm of rage going on in our minds.

170
00:21:16,590 --> 00:21:26,987
Last night I described my own striking example of this when I was doing some walking meditation on retreat, being quite happy until someone came in and started walking near me.

171
00:21:27,647 --> 00:21:29,791
I could have sworn the room went dark.

172
00:21:31,134 --> 00:21:39,527
Because I was being mindful, I could see that the darkening was internal and that my mood had suddenly gone from good humour to bad humour.

173
00:21:40,334 --> 00:21:43,659
but I still had to look out the window to be sure the weather hadn't changed.

174
00:21:44,740 --> 00:21:50,989
I hadn't ever noticed before that my mood could literally colour the visual scene in front of me.

175
00:21:52,310 --> 00:21:58,038
This gave me a striking example of how our sankaras affect our perception of the world.

176
00:22:00,127 --> 00:22:02,991
We can see this when we're feeling dull or lethargic.

177
00:22:04,013 --> 00:22:05,635
All our sense data is blurred.

178
00:22:06,477 --> 00:22:11,183
We'll only vaguely be aware of what's around us, hardly noticing any sounds or sights.

179
00:22:12,326 --> 00:22:17,792
But then if we hear our name called, we're suddenly alert and hear and see everything in detail.

180
00:22:18,994 --> 00:22:27,267
It was the same data falling on our ears and eyes, but experienced differently because of the sankaras of dullness and alertness.

181
00:22:28,883 --> 00:22:33,333
This also underlies the way people can describe the same situation differently.

182
00:22:34,635 --> 00:22:40,009
Say a husband and wife go to talk to a financial advisor about getting a loan for an extension.

183
00:22:41,833 --> 00:22:47,465
Let's say the husband really wants the loan but his wife is not so keen about getting into debt.

184
00:22:49,740 --> 00:23:04,038
When they talk about it afterwards, it's very likely that the wife will remember all the dangers mentioned, but will be vague about any encouraging remarks made, while the husband will have picked up all the encouragement and skimmed over the warnings.

185
00:23:05,500 --> 00:23:12,609
Again, it's the same input data, but being perceived differently because of their different Sankaras.

186
00:23:14,682 --> 00:23:26,732
If we follow the Buddha's advice to see both the sense object and the sense door, we'd be much better at discerning how our subjective stance is colouring the situation.

187
00:23:28,535 --> 00:23:32,218
We get into the habit of asking ourselves, how am I looking?

188
00:23:33,058 --> 00:23:36,080
Am I looking at this with suspicion or with friendliness?

189
00:23:36,862 --> 00:23:37,823
How am I listening?

190
00:23:38,683 --> 00:23:40,846
Am I looking for errors in what's being said?

191
00:23:41,665 --> 00:23:43,508
Am I eager to agree with it all?

192
00:23:46,306 --> 00:23:54,736
When our Sankara, rooted in ignorance, makes contact with the world through any of the sense doors, the wheel has turned halfway around.

193
00:23:55,738 --> 00:24:00,604
And unless we are mindful, it will easily get through the full cycle to cause dukkha.

194
00:24:02,526 --> 00:24:07,352
To prevent this, let's go back to the advice of the Buddha regarding the sense spheres.

195
00:24:08,682 --> 00:24:13,970
One knows the eye and forms and the fetter that arises dependent on both.

196
00:24:15,172 --> 00:24:21,181
One knows the ears and sounds and the fetter that arises dependent on both.

197
00:24:22,182 --> 00:24:25,087
And so on for all the six senses.

198
00:24:26,750 --> 00:24:32,479
Fetter means that which ties us to suffering, to the endless round of birth and death.

199
00:24:33,134 --> 00:24:40,526
So he is here encapsulating all of the links from sense contact onwards which spin us into dukkha.

200
00:24:42,568 --> 00:24:45,252
To recap on the final links of the wheel.

201
00:24:47,076 --> 00:24:54,146
Our system responds to each sense contact by classifying it as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

202
00:24:55,588 --> 00:24:57,571
This is the link of feelings.

203
00:24:59,357 --> 00:25:05,808
Unless we're being mindful, we react to our feelings with desire, aversion or ignoring.

204
00:25:07,311 --> 00:25:08,814
This is the start of the trouble.

205
00:25:10,257 --> 00:25:17,328
We desire more of the pleasant, we want to get rid of what is unpleasant, and we ignore whatever is neutral.

206
00:25:19,231 --> 00:25:24,201
To accomplish these three outcomes, our system then generates a sense of self.

207
00:25:25,430 --> 00:25:32,446
Thoughts of me and mine start to emerge to gather all our motivation towards our new goal.

208
00:25:32,487 --> 00:25:35,074
This is the link of clinging.

209
00:25:36,457 --> 00:25:43,032
In our gardening analogy, the weed has blossomed, it is fully formed and has the stamp of identity.

210
00:25:44,464 --> 00:25:47,328
The next thing it needs to do is sow some seeds.

211
00:25:48,570 --> 00:25:55,520
This is the link of becoming where we decide to speak or act or scheme to fulfil our desires.

212
00:25:56,682 --> 00:26:00,386
We are now exercising our will to change something in the world.

213
00:26:01,910 --> 00:26:14,386
This is crucial to our future happiness because Sankara seeds sown at this point are likely to emerge again at the second point of the wheel to get a new cycle going again in the future.

214
00:26:15,920 --> 00:26:18,303
That's why this step is termed becoming.

215
00:26:19,483 --> 00:26:29,635
Basically, we create the habits which tie us to suffering by acting on our desires and aversions and ignoring what doesn't seem relevant to our agenda.

216
00:26:34,060 --> 00:26:40,068
As a result, we get the next step, the start of some new activity termed birth.

217
00:26:41,549 --> 00:26:45,555
This is the penultimate step in the wheel of dependent origination.

218
00:26:46,278 --> 00:26:52,067
Once we've decided to fulfil a desire for food, we get ourselves over to the cupboard to have a snack.

219
00:26:54,230 --> 00:27:02,162
Every step on the journey, every move of our arm to open the cupboard, and then the biscuit tin, requires an act of will.

220
00:27:03,523 --> 00:27:07,048
The wheel is spinning through hundreds, perhaps thousands of cycles.

221
00:27:08,431 --> 00:27:11,796
Each of these sows another seed for the sankara of greed.

222
00:27:12,788 --> 00:27:21,417
So the new activity we've just started, which is the link of birth and the wheel, allows the Sankara to reproduce itself a hundred or thousand fold.

223
00:27:22,720 --> 00:27:29,467
In our gardening analogy, the weeds has grown into a bramble thicket and is overrunning the garden.

224
00:27:30,368 --> 00:27:34,773
Each flower head is scattering seeds into the wind for future turns of the wheel.

225
00:27:37,497 --> 00:27:40,180
Then comes the final link, dukkha.

226
00:27:41,137 --> 00:27:45,307
We've eaten the packet of biscuits and now our teeth are all gummed up with crumbs.

227
00:27:45,728 --> 00:27:48,634
We feel a bit sick as well as guilty and out of sorts.

228
00:27:49,457 --> 00:27:51,741
The weighing scales is an enemy looming over us.

229
00:27:52,703 --> 00:27:56,633
The pleasure is all gone and only the hangover remains.

230
00:27:58,586 --> 00:28:13,559
In the teaching on the sense spheres, the Buddha is asking us to avoid all the hassle of the second half of the wheel by anchoring our attention at the point of sense contact, knowing that our habitual reactions will fetter us to dukkha.

231
00:28:15,121 --> 00:28:20,705
Desire for pleasure will fetter us to the biscuit tin or the next rung on the ladder of success and fame.

232
00:28:21,967 --> 00:28:28,492
Or it might prompt us to flatter somebody so they will like us, so we get fettered into an unhealthy relationship.

233
00:28:30,396 --> 00:28:34,022
Aversion also ends up attaching us to what we dislike.

234
00:28:34,943 --> 00:28:36,066
It can be hard to believe.

235
00:28:37,127 --> 00:28:43,377
But if there's somebody you really don't want to meet, you'll probably spend your whole day looking out in case they're coming.

236
00:28:44,880 --> 00:28:56,218
A friend once gave the example of going out into a garden and only seeing the clematis that needed pruning and tidying, unable to appreciate the beauty of the rest of the garden.

237
00:28:57,008 --> 00:29:00,213
so her attention was fettered to the overgrown clematis.

238
00:29:01,736 --> 00:29:04,662
Once, I took an acute dislike to someone at a meeting.

239
00:29:05,502 --> 00:29:10,571
For an hour or more, my mind was tracking them, noticing when they came in and out of the room.

240
00:29:11,534 --> 00:29:18,086
I found myself eavesdropping on what they were saying when they were nearby, instead of listening to the conversation in my own group.

241
00:29:18,826 --> 00:29:21,632
Effectively, I was yoked to that person.

242
00:29:24,328 --> 00:29:26,974
How do neutral sensations and thought fetter us?

243
00:29:27,957 --> 00:29:42,067
It's not that we get hooked on the sight of a grey pavement or the background whisper of wind, but we get hooked on the interpretation, this isn't relevant, and the habit of looking for something that will feed our sense of self.

244
00:29:44,848 --> 00:29:55,855
So the habit of ignoring the neutral fetters us to the spicy aspects of our sense contacts, running after pleasure and vainly trying to run away from displeasure.

245
00:29:57,521 --> 00:30:20,913
The more often we experience and reflect upon experience to see how our habitual reactions fetter us to dukkha, the more willing we will be to follow the Buddha's advice to maintain mindfulness at sense contact and the resultant feeling of pleasant, unpleasant and neutral, watching out for the danger and pulling ourselves back from the brink again and again.

246
00:30:23,105 --> 00:30:28,477
His advice to know both the internal and external aspects of sense contact is a great help.

247
00:30:30,039 --> 00:30:41,265
If we are conscious only of the object, the birdsong for example, we will easily be drawn outwards into thoughts about birds and miss our habitual reaction driving these thoughts.

248
00:30:42,545 --> 00:30:55,723
But if we bring attention to the subjective hearing of the birdsong, our attention is already internal and we may catch the pleasure and be much more sensitive to the first signs of desire, aversion or ignoring.

249
00:31:00,371 --> 00:31:04,857
The Buddha stresses that the fetter is separate to our senses and what they perceive.

250
00:31:06,259 --> 00:31:09,884
He gives the analogy of two oxen tied together with a yoke.

251
00:31:11,214 --> 00:31:16,480
The bondage is not due to either of the oxen, but to the yoke.

252
00:31:16,500 --> 00:31:24,790
So when we see something, the fetter is not due to our eyes or to whatever we see, but to the binding power of desire.

253
00:31:24,830 --> 00:31:27,074
This is also important.

254
00:31:28,236 --> 00:31:30,597
We can easily get into blaming this situation.

255
00:31:31,358 --> 00:31:35,964
If only there wasn't so much noise, I could be mindful or blaming ourselves.

256
00:31:36,905 --> 00:31:40,210
If only I could keep my eyes shut, I wouldn't be so distracted.

257
00:31:41,454 --> 00:31:44,679
But neither the noise nor our eyes cause dukkha.

258
00:31:45,720 --> 00:31:52,827
We can relax with all our senses open to the world, with its myriad of sights and sounds and smells and so on.

259
00:31:53,989 --> 00:32:04,580
It's only the third component, the stirrings of desire, aversion, or the way we shy away from reality in an effort to ignore it, that cause the trouble.

260
00:32:05,561 --> 00:32:06,923
The oxen are harmless.

261
00:32:07,724 --> 00:32:10,567
It's only the yoke that binds us to dukkha.

262
00:32:14,480 --> 00:32:24,872
As we bring attention to the sense spheres, we learn to recognise the subtle manifestation of reactivity before this sets us off into actions and reactions.

263
00:32:26,614 --> 00:32:28,717
Eye movements can be helpful in this regard.

264
00:32:29,837 --> 00:32:33,702
I had an example of this when I was on pilgrimage in India with Bhante and others.

265
00:32:34,683 --> 00:32:38,347
For a few days I felt really nauseous following a dose of Deli Belly.

266
00:32:39,308 --> 00:32:44,115
Whenever I tried to focus on a menu, my eyes would wince and hop away from the page.

267
00:32:45,309 --> 00:32:48,354
Then came a long car journey where I got locked into a stupor.

268
00:32:49,355 --> 00:32:52,519
After checking into our new lodgings, the others set off for a meal.

269
00:32:52,558 --> 00:32:56,844
I tagged along, my mind still in its dull stupor.

270
00:32:57,786 --> 00:33:02,672
I only woke up, so to speak, when I found my eyes darting eagerly over the menu.

271
00:33:03,573 --> 00:33:06,195
To my amazement, I realised I had recovered.

272
00:33:07,237 --> 00:33:10,862
I recognised the force moving my eyes around the menu as greed.

273
00:33:12,192 --> 00:33:22,772
Comparing that to the ways my eyes had previously been hopping away from the menu, I saw in retrospect a subtle hostility, as if the menu was an enemy that was threatening me.

274
00:33:25,439 --> 00:33:29,626
I often notice greed at this very early stage when I'm eating mindfully.

275
00:33:30,586 --> 00:33:34,551
My eyes often rest on something neutral while I'm chewing a mouthful of food.

276
00:33:35,614 --> 00:33:41,804
But as I get ready to swallow, my eyes start darting all over my plate, eyeing up the next mouthful.

277
00:33:42,605 --> 00:33:48,375
If I notice this, I can uproot this new manifestation of greed before it makes trouble for me.

278
00:33:49,402 --> 00:33:52,852
Once I notice my eyes popping and darting I have a choice.

279
00:33:52,892 --> 00:33:57,786
I can relax and be mindful of the food in my mouth and the feeling of swallowing.

280
00:33:58,848 --> 00:34:00,795
Mindfulness has uprooted greed.

281
00:34:04,369 --> 00:34:14,173
The wheel has turned as far as eye contact and the resultant feeling of pleasure and whatever little manifestations of greed managed to get my eyes darting all over the plate.

282
00:34:14,916 --> 00:34:20,909
But at that point, mindfulness intervened and the wheel didn't get to turn its full cycle to dukkha.

283
00:34:22,190 --> 00:34:35,440
If I hadn't been mindful of those little eye movements, I would have gobbled my dinner, only vaguely aware of what I was tasting and feeling entirely unsatisfied, would have gone back for second helpings if I could get away with it.

284
00:34:38,795 --> 00:34:43,443
We can also learn to discern unskillful Sankara from the way we are listening.

285
00:34:44,505 --> 00:34:47,048
On one retreat there was a lot of noise from the kitchen.

286
00:34:47,849 --> 00:34:52,759
The teacher noticed that while everyone else complained of the noise, I said it didn't trouble me.

287
00:34:53,780 --> 00:34:59,469
I thought it was my superior mindfulness practice, but the teacher knew better.

288
00:34:59,449 --> 00:35:04,141
He suggested I really listen carefully to sounds during my next meditation.

289
00:35:05,382 --> 00:35:13,661
As it happened it was evening and the kitchen was quiet but a big storm blew up outside and the wind was beating furiously against the house.

290
00:35:14,923 --> 00:35:21,373
As I listened, I became aware of tiny wincing reactions in my face at every loud gust.

291
00:35:22,373 --> 00:35:27,340
I focused attention in the reaction and felt a fleeting pain before each wince.

292
00:35:28,402 --> 00:35:36,213
Then, as I focused on the pain, I became aware that a thought darted through my mind as the pain ran through my face.

293
00:35:37,353 --> 00:35:44,643
To my amazement, the thought was, I didn't hear that, and a lovely feeling of delight followed.

294
00:35:45,889 --> 00:35:48,434
For a while it was incredibly confusing.

295
00:35:49,255 --> 00:35:54,081
My ears were hearing the blasts of wind, but my mind was happily denying this.

296
00:35:56,184 --> 00:36:10,664
After a while my mind started to believe my ears instead of its thoughts, and I had to trade the delightful state of denial for a mind that was made nervous and unhappy by the howling wind and rattling windows.

297
00:36:12,197 --> 00:36:18,065
I was amazed at the power of denial to create a different reality to the one which is actually presenting.

298
00:36:19,306 --> 00:36:24,074
Needless to say, I was horribly upset by the noises in the kitchen next day.

299
00:36:26,076 --> 00:36:31,923
Although this was a painful wake-up call for me, I was also glad of being more in touch with reality.

300
00:36:32,945 --> 00:36:41,817
I felt stronger, more mature, better able to look after myself and had no wish to go back to my cosy state of denial.

301
00:36:43,956 --> 00:36:50,545
Thus, keeping our attention at sense contact lets us see the danger and avoid getting fettered.

302
00:36:51,487 --> 00:36:55,152
It can be very enjoyable, like playing a game with reality.

303
00:36:56,355 --> 00:37:01,762
Our old habits are doing their best to get that yoke around our necks, but we keep dodging and ducking.

304
00:37:03,605 --> 00:37:05,668
Every now and then, of course, we will get caught.

305
00:37:06,748 --> 00:37:10,875
Suppose we notice we've been lost in a haze of worries as we walk through a park.

306
00:37:11,934 --> 00:37:15,699
We need to make a very determined effort to rouse ourselves from this.

307
00:37:17,121 --> 00:37:26,690
We will easily be pulled back into autopilot as our mind will be alive with worrisome thoughts, a million little hooks all trying to drag us back into the haze.

308
00:37:28,052 --> 00:37:33,759
The wheel has the momentum of desire, attachment and becoming behind it now.

309
00:37:34,980 --> 00:37:39,764
It has managed to give birth to lots of worries and to the emotion of anxiety.

310
00:37:43,086 --> 00:37:45,309
Remember our gardening analogy.

311
00:37:46,391 --> 00:37:50,054
The weed has grown into a thicket and sown lots of seeds.

312
00:37:51,135 --> 00:37:55,561
The gardener needs to chop away at the edges before he can get to the core and uproot it.

313
00:37:56,842 --> 00:38:11,440
We need to fortify ourselves with a chop, chop, chop at each new shoot by reminding ourselves of the Dhamma and how necessary it is for us to counter the habitual tendency to live life in the future or past.

314
00:38:12,753 --> 00:38:20,641
We draw ourselves into the present by paying attention to the sights and sounds around us and the feeling of anxiety within.

315
00:38:20,701 --> 00:38:30,610
So we're back at sense contact again and here we can chop away at the thicket, letting each wish to react fizzle itself out.

316
00:38:32,072 --> 00:38:40,701
Eventually we will come to the root of the problem, some pleasant, unpleasant or neutral feeling that we were reacting to.

317
00:38:42,824 --> 00:38:45,987
It can be quite a challenge to hold attention steady here.

318
00:38:47,329 --> 00:38:49,811
Every fibre in our being wants to react.

319
00:38:50,952 --> 00:38:57,900
But if we hold our ground, we'll see through the compulsion and grow a little wiser as well.

320
00:38:59,141 --> 00:39:07,009
Thus, in our future work with the sense spheres, we'll be better equipped to resist the yoke that ties us to dukkha.

321
00:39:10,262 --> 00:39:22,668
In summary then, the teaching on the six sense spheres draws our attention to the link between our inner subjective world and what we normally think of as the outer objective world.

322
00:39:23,998 --> 00:39:32,768
Instead of focusing only on the outer world, this teaching draws our attention inwards to detect also the way we are looking at things.

323
00:39:34,030 --> 00:39:40,376
We discover that our underlying moods and emotions colour our perceptions of the objective world.

324
00:39:41,538 --> 00:39:48,606
In a very real sense, we sense that there is no clear separation between the inner and outer worlds.

325
00:39:50,442 --> 00:40:03,717
Holding attention on the sense spheres, we notice the first stirrings of desire for what attracts us, aversion to what repels us, and the delusion prompting us to ignore what registers as neutral.

326
00:40:04,978 --> 00:40:10,204
Thus we resist the reactivity which sets the latter part of the wheel in motion.

327
00:40:11,967 --> 00:40:16,753
We are resisting the temptation towards new illusions of me and mind.

328
00:40:17,931 --> 00:40:22,112
We are learning to immerse ourselves in the world without clinging.

329
00:40:23,980 --> 00:40:26,693
We are practicing the art of freedom.

